climbs.name: Wile E. Coyote
climbs.fa: Neil Story, Jared Hancock, Robert Williams, Pat Thompson, Paul Dill 2021

content.description: A reachy start leads to juggy pockets and sidepulls. Finish on a short overhanging section using a massive hidden jug to clip the chains.
content.location: The leftmost sport route of the pair on the highly featured face above the approach trail on the right as you enter Coal Bank Hollow.

climbs.name: Trundling Trolls
climbs.fa: Karla Carandang, Ines Truesdale, Jared Hancock, Tom Truesdale  2005

content.description: boulder up to a ledge and follow easier climbing to the anchors
content.location: Third route from far left end of wall.

climbs.name: Thunderclinger
climbs.fa: Tom and Ines Truesdale, Jared Hancock, Karla Carandang, 2005

content.description: This is a fun little climb that is both dynamic and technical.  The crux of the route is at the beginning of the route.  Make a difficult traverse left to gain a nice ledge and crack.  Follow the crack to a funky groove.  Get your groove on to a nice steep finish.  Good varied climb that is worth the hike around.  This line dries fairly quick after a rain.
content.protection: 6 bolts to a two bolt rap anchor.  Rap using a 60m rope.
content.location: The route is up the hill towards the end of the climbing.  Notice a large block that looms above and to the left of this climb.  The large block is part of an adjacent climb Bombardier.  Look for a smooth slab with a short water groove at the top.

content.description: This overhanging route is full of pockets. Finding the right combo makes for a fun ascent.
content.location: Next to Trundling Trolls and also marked on the wall.

content.description: Exposed toprope route under the ledge above the balcony on the far right above the 3rd class gully.

climbs.name: Manteleer
climbs.fa: Mark Ryan, Skip Wolfe, Jared Hancock  2005

content.description: The route follows a small dihedral then goes up to the left. This route is not straight forward but is very enjoyable
content.location: Look for a small bolted dihedral starting 10 feet off the ground.

content.description: follow bolts up over a couple roofs to the face above
Left leaning flake above the exposed ledge on the far right side of Coyote Cliff.
A bouldery start leads to easier climbing until mid-route. A balancy couple moves lead to a thin crimp and a long dynamic move off the crimp to a jug. Easier climbing to the anchors.
content.location: First bolted encounter on the approach. Climbs the yellow/gold pocketed face

content.description: Fun Over Hung route 3 bolts up to ledge.
Short layback crack reminiscent of "Le Petite Bazaar" at Phantasia.
content.location: Located along the right side of the approach trail shortly after making the turn into Coal Bank Hollow.

content.description: Climbs through a bulge to a ledge and then continue up face
content.location: Left of Golden Road about 25 feet.

content.description: Quality climbing on good rock. Begin on a slopey feature then ascend the thin and techy vertical face above then follow a sculpted water groove to a set of intermediate anchors. There is a 3 bolt extension (Muir Power To You) if you need more.
content.location: This fine line is located between Buddhalicious and Golden Road.

content.description: This wandering toprope route is thin and technical with some tricky route finding and a deviously thin section in the middle. It joins the last bolt of Manteleer and shares top anchors with that climb.
Climb the pocketed face between a small arete feature and another arete to the right using plentiful pebbly pockets with many helpful underclings along the way.
content.protection: 4 glue-in bolts + 2 bolt chain/ring top anchor
content.location: Rightmost route of the pair of sport routes encountered along the approach trail prior to reaching the main wall of Coyote Cliff.
